  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the Indian petrol pump scams that everyone needs to be warned about?",
  "response": "There are several scams associated with petrol pumps in India that customers should be aware of to avoid being cheated. Here are some common ones:\n\n1. **Short Fueling**: This is one of the most common scams where the pump attendant either stops the fuel pump before reaching the requested amount or restarts the meter without resetting it, effectively charging for more fuel than actually dispensed.\n\n2. **Distraction Technique**: Attendants may attempt to divert the customer's attention by engaging them in conversation or asking irrelevant questions. During this distraction, they may short-change the amount of fuel dispensed.\n\n3. **Meter Tampering**: Some pumps may have tampered meters that display more fuel dispensed than what is actually delivered. This can be achieved through electronic manipulation or mechanical tampering.\n\n4. **Adulteration**: Fuel adulteration involves mixing petrol or diesel with cheaper substances like kerosene. This not only leads to financial loss but also damages the vehicle's engine over time.\n\n5. **Credit/Debit Card Frauds**: When paying by card, some attendants might note down card details or duplicate the card using skimming devices. Always ensure that transactions happen in your sight.\n\n6. **Cash Back/Coupon Scams**: Sometimes, attendants might promise cash back or discounts for using certain payment methods, only for customers to find that these offers are not genuine or applicable.\n\n7. **Changing Currency Notes**: If you pay with cash, attendants might try to confuse you by claiming you gave a smaller denomination note than you actually did. Always count cash carefully.\n\n8. **Hose Manipulation**: In some cases, the hose may be manipulated to retain some fuel, preventing it from reaching your tank when the pump is activated.\n\nTo protect yourself from these scams, consider the following tips:\n\n- Always check the fuel meter before and after fueling.\n- Keep an eye on the attendant and the meter throughout the fueling process.\n- Insist on a printed receipt and verify it against the meter reading.\n- Use payment methods that offer protection against fraud, like mobile wallets or secure card payments.\n- Be cautious of any unsolicited offers or discounts.\n\nBy staying vigilant and informed, you can minimize the risk of falling victim to these scams.",
